Below is a LaTeX “lecture notes” write-up based on **Section 4.1 (Sampling and Surveys)** of your PDF, with **worked numerical examples** and a **selection of paraphrased exercises** from that section. fileciteturn5file1L105-L110 fileciteturn5file1L254-L257 fileciteturn5file1L887-L973

```latex
\documentclass[11pt]{article}

\usepackage[margin=1in]{geometry}
\usepackage{amsmath,amssymb,amsthm}
\usepackage{enumitem}
\usepackage{hyperref}
\usepackage{booktabs}

% --- theorem environments (lecture-notes style) ---
\theoremstyle{definition}
\newtheorem{definition}{Definition}[section]
\newtheorem{example}{Example}[section]
\newtheorem{remark}{Remark}[section]

\newcommand{\N}{\mathbb{N}}
\newcommand{\PP}{\mathbb{P}}
\newcommand{\binomNn}[2]{\binom{#1}{#2}}

\title{Lecture Notes: Sampling and Surveys (Section 4.1)}
\author{}
\date{}

\begin{document}
\maketitle
\tableofcontents

\section{Populations, samples, and sample surveys}

\begin{definition}[Population and sample]
The \emph{population} is the entire group we want information about. A \emph{sample} is the part of the population from which we actually collect data, and we use the sample to draw conclusions about the population.
\end{definition}

\begin{definition}[Census and sample survey]
A \emph{census} attempts to collect data from every member of the population. A \emph{sample survey} uses an organized plan to choose a sample that represents a specific population.
\end{definition}

\subsection{Planning checklist}
In a well-posed sampling problem, you should be able to answer:
\begin{enumerate}[label=\arabic*.]
  \item \textbf{Who is the population?} (be precise)
  \item \textbf{What variables are measured?} (define them operationally)
  \item \textbf{How is the sample chosen?} (this determines what you can trust)
\end{enumerate}

\begin{example}[Population vs.\ sample with numbers]
A factory produces a \emph{batch} of $N=500$ items. A quality inspector tests $n=8$ items from that batch.
\begin{itemize}
  \item Population: all $500$ items in the batch.
  \item Sample: the $8$ tested items.
\end{itemize}
\end{example}

\section{How to sample badly: bias, convenience samples, voluntary response}

\begin{definition}[Bias]
A study design shows \emph{bias} if it systematically favors certain outcomes (so it tends to overestimate or underestimate the truth in a consistent direction).
\end{definition}

\begin{definition}[Convenience sample]
A \emph{convenience sample} is obtained by choosing individuals who are easiest to reach.
\end{definition}

\begin{definition}[Voluntary response sample]
A \emph{voluntary response sample} consists of people who choose themselves by responding to a general invitation. Such samples are often biased because people with strong opinions are more likely to respond.
\end{definition}

\begin{remark}[Always state the direction of the bias]
When asked how a design could lead to bias, do not stop at ``it is biased.'' State \emph{which way} it likely pushes the result (overestimate vs.\ underestimate) and why.
\end{remark}

\begin{example}[Convenience sampling can overestimate]
You want the mean number of hours of homework done last week by all students at a school (population).
You sample the first $n=30$ students you see in the library and compute the sample mean:
\[
\bar{x}=\frac{1}{30}\sum_{i=1}^{30} x_i.
\]
Suppose the 30 reported hours sum to $ \sum x_i = 240$; then $\bar{x}=240/30=8$ hours.
Because library visitors may be more studious than average, $\bar{x}=8$ is plausibly an \emph{overestimate} of the population mean.
\end{example}

\begin{example}[Voluntary response can be dominated by strong opinions]
An online poll about a school policy gets $n=1000$ clicks. Suppose $720$ click ``Yes,'' so $\hat p = 720/1000 = 0.72$.
Even though $n$ is large, the sample is self-selected; the $0.72$ may be far from the true population proportion.
\end{example}

\section{How to sample well: random sampling and the SRS}

\subsection{The guiding principle}
To reduce bias from human choice and self-selection, we let \emph{impersonal chance} choose the sample.

\begin{definition}[Simple random sample (SRS)]
A \emph{simple random sample (SRS)} of size $n$ is chosen so that \emph{every set of $n$ individuals} in the population has the same chance to be the sample selected.
\end{definition}

\subsection{Basic probability facts implied by the SRS definition}
Let the population size be $N$ and the sample size be $n$.
\begin{itemize}
\item Number of distinct size-$n$ samples: $\binom{N}{n}$.
\item Each particular size-$n$ sample has probability:
\[
\PP(\text{a specific sample is chosen})=\frac{1}{\binom{N}{n}}.
\]
\item Each individual has selection probability:
\[
\PP(\text{a given individual is selected})=\frac{n}{N}.
\]
\end{itemize}

\begin{example}[Compute selection probabilities]
A class has $N=50$ students. You want an SRS of $n=5$ students.
\[
\PP(\text{a given student is selected})=\frac{5}{50}=0.10.
\]
There are $\binom{50}{5}$ possible samples, and each specific 5-person set has probability $1/\binom{50}{5}$.
\end{example}

\section{Selecting an SRS in practice: labels and random digits}

\begin{definition}[Table of random digits (concept)]
A random-digit source is a long sequence of digits $0$--$9$ behaving like repeated independent draws where each digit is equally likely to be $0,1,\dots,9$.
\end{definition}

\subsection{Two-step procedure (works with a digit table or a computer)}
\begin{enumerate}[label=\textbf{Step \arabic*:}, leftmargin=*]
\item \textbf{Label.} Assign each population member a numerical label of equal length.
\item \textbf{Generate/Read digits.} Read consecutive blocks of digits of the appropriate length. Keep labels that are valid and not repeated. Skip invalid blocks and duplicates. Continue until you have $n$ distinct labels.
\end{enumerate}

\begin{example}[Worked SRS selection using a made-up digit stream]
You have $N=28$ hotels. Label them $01,02,\dots,28$. We want $n=4$ distinct labels.

Suppose the digit stream (grouped into two-digit blocks) begins:
\[
31,\ 05,\ 16,\ 48,\ 17,\ 17,\ 02,\ 29,\ 20,\ 05,\ 14,\ 08,\dots
\]
We scan left to right:
\begin{itemize}
\item $31$ (invalid: $>28$) skip.
\item $05$ keep (sample: $\{05\}$).
\item $16$ keep (sample: $\{05,16\}$).
\item $48$ invalid skip.
\item $17$ keep (sample: $\{05,16,17\}$).
\item next $17$ is a repeat skip.
\item $02$ keep (sample: $\{05,16,17,02\}$). Stop: we have 4 labels.
\end{itemize}
So the chosen SRS corresponds to hotels $02,05,16,17$ (in the order found).
\end{example}

\begin{remark}[With vs.\ without replacement]
Some random-number tools sample \emph{with replacement} by default (duplicates can appear). For an SRS \emph{without replacement}, duplicates must be discarded and replaced by continuing the random process until distinct labels are obtained.
\end{remark}

\section{Other sampling methods: stratified, cluster, multistage, systematic}

\subsection{Stratified random sampling}
\begin{definition}[Stratified random sample; strata]
A \emph{stratified random sample} is formed by dividing the population into groups called \emph{strata} (groups similar in a way relevant to the variable), taking an SRS within each stratum, and combining the subsamples.
\end{definition}

\begin{example}[Proportional stratified sampling with arithmetic]
A school has 1000 students:
\[
\text{Freshmen }400,\quad \text{Sophomores }300,\quad \text{Juniors }200,\quad \text{Seniors }100.
\]
You want a stratified sample of $n=100$ with proportional allocation.
Compute each stratum's fraction and sample size:
\[
n_F = 100\cdot \frac{400}{1000}=40,\quad
n_S = 100\cdot \frac{300}{1000}=30,\quad
n_J = 100\cdot \frac{200}{1000}=20,\quad
n_{Sr} = 100\cdot \frac{100}{1000}=10.
\]
Then take an SRS of 40 freshmen, 30 sophomores, 20 juniors, 10 seniors, and combine them.
\end{example}

\subsection{Cluster sampling}
\begin{definition}[Cluster sample; clusters]
To take a \emph{cluster sample}, divide the population into clusters (ideally each cluster resembles the whole population on a smaller scale), choose an SRS of clusters, and include \emph{all} individuals in the chosen clusters.
\end{definition}

\begin{example}[Cluster sample with numbers]
A school has 40 homerooms of 25 students each ($40\times 25=1000$ students).
To survey about $n\approx 200$ students, choose $8$ homerooms at random (an SRS of clusters), then survey all $8\times 25=200$ students in those homerooms.
\end{example}

\begin{remark}[Strata vs.\ clusters (do not confuse)]
\begin{itemize}
\item In \textbf{stratification}, each stratum is internally similar; strata differ from each other in relevant ways.
\item In \textbf{clustering}, each cluster should (ideally) mirror the population; you then sample clusters for convenience.
\end{itemize}
\end{remark}

\subsection{Multistage sampling}
Large surveys often combine methods in stages (for logistics): e.g.\ select large geographic units, then neighborhoods, then small local clusters within neighborhoods.

\subsection{Systematic random sampling (often a final-stage tool)}
A common recipe is:
\[
k=\frac{N}{n}\quad (\text{sampling interval, assume }k\in \N).
\]
Choose a random start $s\in\{1,2,\dots,k\}$, then take
\[
s,\ s+k,\ s+2k,\ \dots,\ s+(n-1)k.
\]

\begin{example}[Systematic sample with working]
Choose $n=6$ addresses from a list of $N=120$.
Then $k=N/n = 120/6 = 20$.
Pick a random start, say $s=7$. The systematic sample is:
\[
7,\ 27,\ 47,\ 67,\ 87,\ 107.
\]
Each address has the same chance to be selected (because the start is random), but not every 6-subset is possible, so it is \emph{not} an SRS.
\end{example}

\section{Inference and what can go wrong in real surveys}

\subsection{Inference and sampling variability}
\begin{definition}[Inference (informal)]
\emph{Inference} means drawing conclusions about a population using data from a sample.
\end{definition}

Even for a good random sample, sample-to-sample results vary by chance. This is \emph{sampling variability}. Polls often summarize expected sampling variability with a \emph{margin of error}. As a rough principle: larger random samples are typically more precise than smaller ones.

\begin{remark}[Preview: variability scales like $1/\sqrt{n}$]
In later work, you will see formulas like
\[
\mathrm{SE}(\hat p)\approx \sqrt{\frac{p(1-p)}{n}},
\quad\text{so typical error shrinks on the order of } \frac{1}{\sqrt{n}}.
\]
For now, remember: increasing $n$ reduces random variation, but does \emph{not} automatically fix bias.
\end{remark}

\subsection{Sampling errors vs.\ nonsampling errors}
\begin{definition}[Sampling frame]
A \emph{sampling frame} is the list (or mechanism) from which the sample is actually drawn.
\end{definition}

\begin{definition}[Undercoverage]
\emph{Undercoverage} occurs when some groups in the population are left out of the process of choosing the sample (often because the sampling frame misses them).
\end{definition}

\begin{definition}[Nonsampling errors]
\emph{Nonsampling errors} are errors not caused by the randomness of selecting a sample; they can occur even in a census (e.g.\ nonresponse, measurement/recording errors, response bias, wording effects).
\end{definition}

\begin{definition}[Nonresponse]
\emph{Nonresponse} occurs when an individual chosen for the sample cannot be contacted or refuses to participate.
\end{definition}

\begin{remark}[Nonresponse vs.\ voluntary response]
Nonresponse happens \emph{after} a sample has been selected. A voluntary response poll is self-selected at the start; participants ``opt in,'' so the core problem there is selection bias rather than nonresponse.
\end{remark}

\subsection{Response bias and question effects}
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Response bias:} a systematic pattern of inaccurate answers (e.g.\ social desirability, faulty memory, interviewer effects).
\item \textbf{Question wording:} leading or confusing wording can strongly alter results.
\item \textbf{Question order:} earlier questions can prime later answers.
\end{itemize}

\begin{example}[Computing a nonresponse rate]
A phone survey dials $45{,}956$ selected numbers, but completes only $5{,}029$ interviews.
\[
\text{Response rate}=\frac{5029}{45956}\approx 0.1094\approx 10.94\%.
\]
\[
\text{Nonresponse rate}=1-0.1094\approx 0.8906\approx 89.06\%.
\]
A high nonresponse rate can bias results if responders differ systematically from nonresponders.
\end{example}

\section*{Exercises (selected and paraphrased from Section 4.1)}
\addcontentsline{toc}{section}{Exercises (selected and paraphrased from Section 4.1)}

\begin{enumerate}[label=\textbf{4.1.\arabic*}, leftmargin=*]

\item \textbf{Population vs.\ sample (business survey).}
A student newspaper randomly chooses 150 local businesses from a phone directory and mails them a questionnaire; 73 respond.
Identify the population and the sample(s). (Be explicit about what ``sample'' refers to.)

\item \textbf{Population vs.\ sample (customer satisfaction).}
A store had 45{,}000 credit-card purchasers last month. It randomly mails surveys to 1{,}000 of them; 137 return the form.
Identify the population and the sample(s). What practical issue appears here?

\item \textbf{Call-in poll bias.}
A media outlet runs a paid call-in poll on whether a policy should be tougher, with separate numbers for ``Yes'' and ``No.''
Explain why the resulting sample is almost certainly biased. What kind of sampling method is it?

\item \textbf{Letters to a congresswoman.}
A congress office receives 1{,}128 letters about a proposed bill; 871 letters oppose it.
Should you conclude that most voters oppose the bill? Explain the statistical issue in plain language.

\item \textbf{Large online poll does not guarantee trust.}
An online poll asks a yes/no question; roughly 44\% click ``Yes,'' 50\% click ``No,'' and the rest click ``Don't know,'' with more than 30{,}000 total responses.
Why can the result still be untrustworthy despite the large $n$?

\item \textbf{Online magazine poll.}
A magazine invites readers to vote online on whether cell-phone use while driving should be banned. The published results are 85\% ``Yes,'' 15\% ``No.''
(a) What sampling method is being used?
(b) Explain why it is biased. Is 85\% likely higher or lower than the population truth? Why?

\item \textbf{Early-arrivals survey (sleep).}
A student surveys the first 100 students to arrive at school and gets an average of 7.2 hours of sleep last night.
(a) What sampling method is this?
(b) Explain the likely direction of bias and why.

\item \textbf{Mall sampling.}
Explain why interviewing mall shoppers---even many of them---is not a reliable way to estimate a population unemployment rate.

\item \textbf{Choosing an SRS from a roster.}
You want an SRS of 5 students from a class roster.
Describe precisely how you would label students and use a random-digit source to select 5 distinct labels (show how you handle invalid labels and repeats).

\item \textbf{Random digits: where to start.}
If you repeatedly use a fixed digit table, why is it a bad idea to always start reading at the same line/position?

\item \textbf{Random digits: true/false with justification.}
Decide whether each statement about random digits is true or false, and briefly justify.
(a) ``Each row must contain exactly four 0s if it is random.''
(b) ``Any specific two-digit block (like 00) has probability $1/100$.''
(c) ``The block 0000 cannot appear because it looks non-random.''

\item \textbf{Factory quality check (iPhones).}
A factory produces 1{,}000 phones in a day. Managers want to inspect 20 phones.
(a) Why can it be difficult to get an SRS of 20 in this setting?
(b) Why is inspecting the \emph{last} 20 phones a bad idea?
(c) Another plan is to inspect every 50th phone. Explain why this is not an SRS.

\item \textbf{Is it an SRS? (equal individual chance is not enough).}
A company has 2{,}000 male and 500 female engineers. It takes a stratified sample of 200 males and 50 females, so each engineer has probability $1/10$ of selection.
Is this sample an SRS? Explain carefully.

\item \textbf{Systematic sampling: equal chance but not SRS.}
A systematic method chooses a random start in the first $k$ items, then takes every $k$-th item.
Explain why each individual can have equal selection probability, yet the method is not an SRS.

\item \textbf{Undercoverage from a sampling frame.}
A survey samples households using a telephone directory as the frame.
Explain how undercoverage can occur and how it might bias results.

\item \textbf{Nonresponse rate and bias direction.}
A survey makes 45{,}956 calls and completes 5{,}029 interviews.
(a) Compute the nonresponse rate.
(b) Give a plausible way nonresponse could bias an estimate of \emph{average miles driven per day}, and state the likely direction.

\item \textbf{Wording bias.}
For each proposed question, comment on whether it is clear and whether it is slanted toward a desired response. If problematic, rewrite it neutrally.
(You may use examples involving emotionally loaded facts, multi-claim prompts, or heavy jargon.)
\end{enumerate}

\end{document}
```

